headline: Data Analyst nanodegree
reviewBody:
Initially, I wanted to give 4.5 starts but as it doesn't allow half starts I gave 5.

I had studied Data Analyst nanodegree.
The video lessons are very good and goes very much into detail. So, much detail that I had to skip some lessons as I already had knowledge in it.

The assignments are not that easy and really tests your skills and don't expect them to be lenient on you for passing the module for the sake of marking it. I had to submit one of my assignments 6 times before they passed me which is good because this is how you learn when you are challenged. 

However, they need to improve their description of assignment projects and need to be more clear of what they are expecting.

headline: Best Way to Find a New Job
reviewBody: I am very thankful for Udacity and its nanodegree programs.  I have a pretty technical background, but limited experience in the AI/ML realm.  I started applying for jobs over a year ago that would be more involved with AI/ML, but could not receive any offers because I did not have that much professional experience applying AI/ML techniques.  It came to the point that I had to decide whether to continue with my current job for the long term and not pursue my passion for AI/ML or take a temporary step back from applying for jobs and take some courses that could show companies that, even though I was not applying AI/ML professionally, I am interested enough to learn about these techniques independently.  I found out about Udacity and completed taking the Deep Learning and Computer Vision nanodegree programs.  Within six months of starting these courses, I received two offers from companies doing AI/ML work, and plan to begin my new job next week.  The Udacity courses give you a very strong foundation in any topic you want to learn.  Since they are only meant to take a few month to complete each nanodegree, clearly they cannot dig deep into the minor details about how some algorithms work, but they do provide immense amount of additional resources for the user to read in case they want to learn more about a certain topic.  Again I want to thank Udacity so much for these courses, searching for a job is extremely stressful and frustrating, but knowing I have strong AI/ML background now gave me the confidence to speak intelligently during my interviews and get a new job!

headline: Taking advantage of a student's personal misery
reviewBody:
I have taken 3 paid nano degrees from Udacity. Their quality of content is really good and I enjoyed them. 

However, their policies are awful. During my third nanodegree, initially, some of my extended family members tested positive for covid. Then I got it and also my wife and kid. I had a horrid time managing everything. And to my bad luck, I and my immediate family got infected twice from Covid within a span of 45 days.  Obviously I wasn't in a position to continue.
Hence I requested them to put my access on hold for 45 days ( the access was for 3 months ). I wasn't even asking for an extension, just that the access to be put on hold so that I can work on it after my personal health issues get resolved.

After multiple emails, all they have done is to extend the access by 15 days. Thats what they said the best they can do as per policy. Is policies are made for people or the other way round. How can someone be so insensitive? Taking advantage of a student's personal misery. 
I can't recommend this to anyone unfortunately

headline: Udacity would never disappoint you

headline: This is the place I have been looking…
reviewBody:
This is the place I have been looking for. 

1- I want to learn great technical skills from a professional of people online, with good projects + professional mentors who also could answer my questions not only about the courses/projects but also about career options. That feeling makes me no lonely.

I bought several courses from Udemy(comperatively cheaper) however all I see is that a guy uploads a course, and his course is at the top, competing with the others. However, all he does better than others is "Search Engine Optimaziation" inside Udemy. Nothing more...

But at Udacity, I shied away from purchasing a course which was more expensive becuase all I though that if that course would not teach me anythin? and that feeling made me feel afraid of spending my money for nothing, and feeling like a fraud.

Buttt untilll.. they offered me a 30 days free offer, and now I entered a course I am most passionate with it, and I learned a lot of things during that 'lockdown period' also. I am not wasting my time exactly.

Now after the trial is over, the course is expected to finish(on demand) within 6 months, and I will just keep my subscription by paying. That was an amazing offer from you.

Thank you Udacity

headline: AVOID AT ALL COSTS
reviewBody:
AVOID AT ALL COSTS
I paid over £200 for a course which later turns into and £80 a month subscription (which was not mentioned before i paid for the course). On top of all that the course was so slow an uninformative, they barely brush over each topic then leave it to you to figue out on your own (with the help of google). After all this i eventually gave up once the subscription started. For someone who is on the autisic spectrum i felt there was no help or support for this course then once i contacted udacity through the live chat to cancel the person i spoke to was so rude and condescending then once i had cancelled he insulted me. I have all the evidence but cannot contact anyone a udacity as they make it nearbon impossible to contact them. Awful website, awful service awful courses and an awful company.

headline: Nanodegree with Outdated info & broken links
reviewBody:
Started android developers nanodegree. I'm so glad I didn't pay for the full program of 3 months.

Most of the program is from 2015 with outdated info, as android development is changing rapidly some of the info there is not correct. Also most of the links to the additional information are broken/404. It makes me feel like I'm paying for an abandoned Nanodegree program. It takes a few hours to work on links and updating info after the video with texts with up-to-date info isn't that hard really. Udacity disappointed.
Obviously the didn't refund the money because of the time interval I had, been studying for 2 weeks after seeing too many broken/outdated info just fed up. Feels like a beta tester reporting all of this stuff but I'm still paying for it. Not funny.

NOT recommended to anyone who has a limited time

headline: The best online learning platform
reviewBody:
As a developer I am learning whole my life - from YouTube, from paid single topic courses, from free courses, from blog posts etc... 
The nanodegree is what fits my learning style best -  everything is prepared for you - step by step, course after course, video after video, project after project. Previously I had to follow online advises - first you learn this topic, then the other topic, then the next topic etc. With the nanodegree I just follow a well thought learning path - multiple courses and several projects.
* the nanodegree program itself is well though, clear learning path, everything is easy to follow
* the courses are great, great video quality, great graphics, great content
* the projects help me a lot. Instead of just watching the videos and thinking that I know everything already, the projects actually are forcing me (no projects, no graduation :)) to do some real thinking, and not lie to myself - the projects often prove me wrong :)
Great work, Udacity!

headline: Overall good and impressed with curriculum but it's expensive.
reviewBody:
There is a lot of interactive learning. I liked the review and feedback system more than I thought. It makes me feel like I'm in a real classroom:)
1. Project review and feedback system. A detailed report for my work, nicely formatted and easy to understand.
2. Timely reminders for study
3. Engaging study material
4. Good reference links are attached in study material for further researches and the same is attached in project reviews by examiners.
5. Shares progress summary which lets e know the number of projects I have completed, my engagements in the community, and how far I have reached.
6. Not everything is served on a plate to eat, projects are designed in such a way it would require little research, and instructors and community are always available for help.
7. There is also support for how to make your LinkedIn profile appear nice & professional and make one able to stand out in front of job recruiters.
8. It's expensive.

headline: Great contents, slow progress. Need to pay for extra months.
reviewBody:
Great contents, slow progress. So you need to pay for extra months (i.e., after your bundle comes the monthly renewal). Also please note, monthly renewal is set as automated. So remember to cancel before.

Some glitches (outdated exercise results) slowed my progress. You need mentors' help to get going. Thing is it usually takes 3/4 questions & answers to get a more or less clear picture of what you need. This slows down your progress as they do not reply instantly. Some mentors are good, others give you vague answers (it looks like they want to gain time).

If your level of programming is good already, I recommend a Nanodegree with them. If you need to learn you'd be better off to learn from other platforms and get back there just to claim your Nanodegree title.

headline: Udacity NLP Nanodegree senteneces tagging project
reviewBody:
I was really excited to go through the first NLP Nanodegree project for sentences tagging. It was an awesome experience to see the Markov Models and Bayes probability laws are used in these types of applications. They are really the base for multiple applications in various domains from financial forecasts to health care. The explanations and theoretical approach of the course lecturers were exactly what you needed to dive in the code and implement. Also the reviews were
top drawer, since I found out some great improvements I can make to my code in a pythonic fashion.

headline: Worst learning provider I have ever seen
reviewBody: The quality of the content is so bad that average free learning resources are so much better. Especially that the entire course is ridden with mistakes a and poor coding standards - the source Git repository was not updated since May 2019! What is worse the entire system is designed to rip you off since the designated completion time needs to be easily tripled to cover the core lessons and you pay for each additional month. The platform is also super glitchy and it is impossible to get in touch with anybody from Udacity (I am not taking about mentors since they have nothing to do with how the platform works) - because of that I never received the AWS credits which are part of the product. Avoid at all costs

headline: Instant reply & careful review
reviewBody:
I've passed first project. Instant reply and careful review, supported relevant resources, are above expectations. Good to know what I've learned. 

Practice makes perfect, and project is a good idea. Moreover, explaining by example, pointing a point for analysis. helps mind test and work better. Thought lessons are simple, I hope it is supported by an optional "work book" to apply and test many exercises, and this point to be optional. But examples (visual, written, and watched) should be for every point. May there be a certain book for "examples" as well. 

Questions of learners, and answers in the platform, helped me save time, and there's still much to know, In-Sha'-Allah. I hope we collaborate to give advice on national or global scale, work on it to apply. what we learn. Sharing is a best investment, and a best motive. 

The idea is for everywhere, every country. I hope you utilize it well.

headline: I'm very much enjoying it and think…
reviewBody:
I'm very much enjoying it and think it's great that it provides an introduction to many essential skills, such as HTML, CSS, Javascript and Python, plus the chapters about Shell and Git. 

I would, however, change the Nanodegree name to "Programming Fundamentals" to make it sound more professional, as "Introduction to programming" doesn't do it justice and sounds too amateurish. 

To add to one's LinkedIn or CV, "Certificate in Introduction to Programming" just sounds awful and reminds of one of those cheap and poorly designed Udemy courses.
On the other hand, "Certificate in Programming Fundamentals" sounds way better and conveys that idea that one possesses solid core skills that can be built upon.

headline: The program is a good program
reviewBody: The program is going well, thanks for giving me the opportunity to share. One thing I would improve in this program is around data and if the data is US o EU based. For example, distance was not clear if it was KM o MILES. Also some exercises don't mention the importance of cleaning the data enough. Maybe in text, but I would have expected a video of the teacher explicitly asking for this. Also, this course requires "basic knowledge" of Tableau and SQL. Would be great to have a "mini test" before starting so we the students could evaluate if we have this "basic knowledge". If we do, we can continue, if not, derive people to the specific courses (which BTW are free in Udacity) for study. This feedback is just things that could improve. The course again is great and I'm enjoying and learning and really happy with the experience. Hope this feedback helps!

headline: It's been an amazing experience so far
reviewBody: It's been an amazing experience so far. Before now, I've always wanted to write a blog to talk about my projects, but I have always held back as I didn't really know how or where to start from, and also the fear of being criticised for a bad post. However, this program has given me the push, direction and confidence to write more posts to show case my work to non-technical audience. I wish I knew the tips I've learned so far long ago. Now I feel like dropping a post weekly. The feedback I received from Udacity on my first project, is mind-boggling. Well detailed, and lots of pointers to extra reading materials. Amazing. Looking forward to the rest of the courses.

headline: This is my first Udacity course and it…
reviewBody:
This is my first Udacity course and it exceeds all my expectations so far! I really enjoy it. What I especially appreciate is what I call the "digest approach" when introducing new complex technologies: 
1. "This is what it basically is, dont worry about the details for now." This helps my focus.
2. Minimal example that lets me see the benefit of using such technology immediately.
3. Expanding a bit more but not in an overwhelming way.
4. Providing links and recommending resources so I can explore deeper if want to.

headline: Of Beginnings and Project Structures
reviewBody: The first project was a great start to grasp the end-to-end ml pipeline. However, since my last encounter with a project for a udacity nanodegree things seem to have changed. The degree of difficulty seems to have decreased, or my skills have improved. Either way, this could be remedied by making the subsequent projects progressively difficult with respect to one particular stage of the machine learning process; just have the student explore one or two alternative methods of achieving their goal. You could randomly assign different approaches to explore than the base one. For example, in the 'Creating a Sentiment Analysis Web App',  a student could be asked to replace the processing function such that it used word2vec and another student could be asked to implement glove. This could be made an optional part and included in the rubric accordingly. What it could also do is promote some discussion in the chat regarding these approaches. But this is also just a personal opinion. The project does its job of introducing us to the SageMaker API and all the stages involved in the Machine Learning pipeline right up to deployment really well. The project also gives one a beginner friendly understanding of using the model in a simple web app that is deployed to Amazon Lambda and connected via Amazon API Gateway.

headline: I've went into the Udacity program and…
reviewBody:
I've went into the Udacity program and trusted in these positive reviews of the site, here is my experience.
1. Don't trust their vague refund policy, you will not get your money back if you place your credit card.
2. Don't expect human interaction, they only have a forum and there is no direct contact with the tutor.
3. Don't expect solid explanation of material or to be provided references to aid you on your journey.

I wouldn't recommend this for people who want to grow, it is nice for people who want a certificate if their employer recognizes them.

headline: Totally disappointed - Don't Recommend
reviewBody:
Totally disappointed (Digital Marketing Nanodegree). These are a few of the major reasons:

1. It was hard to understand the person on the video. I was expecting a person with clear English and better pronunciation.

2. The videos are hosted on Youtube. They are unlisted YouTube videos. Can you imagine paying 1500 dollars for a course while the author behind it is using "unlisted youtube videos" to teach students? It felt very unprofessional.

3. Uses examples and case studies from 2010. Please use recent case studies. 

4. The refund policy: You have only two days to decide if you want to continue doing the course or not. That was the last straw for me. The course maker was not behind their program. They are not sure if the users would like their program or not. I wanted to browse the course without the fear of not being able to get the full refund. It was not even 24 hours, and the staff told me that I had a couple of minutes left to decide or I don't get any refund at all. 

5. I can go on, but I think I have already made my point.

headline: Definitely the kind of Intro I needed…
reviewBody:
Definitely the kind of Intro I needed to finally get started on learning how to program. I don't think I'd be exaggerating, if I say that without basic knowledge of programming, it seems almost impossible to find an entry point to this "world". 
This Nanodegree program made that step almost seem easy. 

Thumbs up!

Only negative aspect for me is, that its not possible after completing a lesson like "Intro to HTML", you're not able to go back, and review the practices and videos to refresh the knowledge. I understand that after completing the whole degree it will be locked, but why lock it WHILE I'm enrolled? You only get a really watered down summary of the whole lesson. 

Thumbs down!

So for everyone enrolling, I can only recommend to keep writing a personal, detailed summary as you progress through each lesson. 

But still, all in all a great Intro, easy to access, and made fun with all the small, practical exercises and hands on examples.

headline: Very disappointing especially when so expensive
reviewBody: I was asked to review this course fairly at the start and gave it 4 at the time. Unfortunately the truth is that was based on the lectures that were within 14 day money back policy. After that majority of the content is a "puppet show" - someone just talking to you with extreme gesticulation, majority of videos have no visualization tools, no real examples, no real graphs - just someone talking. All examples are made up with unrealistic numbers (like prices being numbers from 1 to 5) and the methods shown are deemed as "not working any more" - and there is non technical or sentimental analysis whatsoever apart from some general momentum strategy or break trough theory. To be fair - mentors answer quicker and only some of them seem not to read your questions, others will really give solid help.

reviewBody:
Udacity though expects everyone to be very good in data structures and algorithms are not beginner-friendly courses for most of the courses they offer.

The beginner paid courses offered by Udacity is the best I have ever experienced from learning and satisfaction point of view.

Though Udacity fails to guide you through the data structures and algorithms understanding of intermediate and advanced courses and though it presumes you already have at least a very professional background on these courses, it is a very good course which simulates like a real job environment situation.

headline: Great instructors and curriculum
reviewBody:
The videos are very informative and have good lengths. The solutions provided are always helpful to complete the assignments and projects.
I much prefer doing my work locally in my IDE (PyCharm). However, this has been difficult because installing psycopg2 (a PostgreSQL package) was laborious. Using the Udacity online workspace, while I appreciate all that was built into it, just lacks easy navigation and code-completion, which an IDE has for a heavy project like project 1.
The Knowledge center had lots of useful information. I just had to be willing to take the time to use it, but its search functions are well built.
The curriculum structure is great. I think it's encouraging.
I like the habit of 30 days of Udacity. Though I don't read all emails/messages from the social media staff member, I read at least half of them, which is uplifting that humans are behind the scenes cheering us all on. 
I liked the Slack channel that was in my DSND in 2018. I use the chat channel and it is quite good, but still tricky to navigate regularly.
The integration with Facebook is a great idea!

headline: I think I'm in a good position to critique Udacity.
reviewBody: I think I'm in a good position to critique Udacity. I've taken a course through Shaw Academy, Thinkable and Udacity. Shaw Academy only allows you to access 2 classes a week. Udacity allows you progress at your own rate. Shaw Academy presented info as a static presentation, quizzes and challenges optional. With Udacity, information is presented as video and static which makes it easier to comprehend. Quizzes reinforce what you've learned and when you answer in error, an explanation is provided but the answer is not given until you get it. Nice.

headline: Well taught lessons and fast mentor replies
reviewBody: The lessons were well taught, and the quizzes and project were completely based on the lessons which are a huge plus. Mentors respond very quickly and the feedback is thorough, which is fantastic. I also really liked the 30-day challenge, that does really help you stay on top of your learning. However, I found that the time frame of 3 months, which was the time frame to complete the program for the bundle I paid for, is too short for someone who spends 1-2 hours a day studying. The SQL concepts alone take time to sink in and only knowing how they work well is how I'd be able to produce code that's accurate and that works. I'd say that my only disappointment is the time frame expected to submit the first project, as well as how quickly the structure of the course assumes you'd be to complete each part. Everything else was great!

headline: Not worth it
reviewBody:
I'm on the Front End Web Development Nanodegree and the content isn't great, videos lack detailed explanations and more often than not there's research to be made elsewhere. The projects are great for practicing, but having to constantly research and troubleshoot is very time consuming. I don't believe is worth the money. 

Their customer service is also not good. I joined in January through a $714 for 4 months offer, but I couldn't start straight away. The day before the offer was expiring I went to buy it and asked them to delay my start day 2 weeks, so that I didn't lose that study time. They said that it wasn't possible, so I went ahead and bought it anyway. Afterwards I saw that they extended the offer for some weeks, so I could have bought it 2 weeks after without losing any study time. Noone bothered to tell me, though. I know I should have gone back to claim but I didn't have time.

Also, it is not possible to cancel without chatting with a rep, and as soon as they see you leaving they send you a canned response offering a "75% discount" on their $399 monthly fee, which is not what I am paying (my deal is for $199 a month, like most). So, they are clearly just offering a 50% discount instead. When I asked for a 75% discount on the actual amount I am paying it was denied.

All in all I don't think is a good product, service or company.

headline: udacity Business Analytics Nanodegree: not worth the money
reviewBody:
Pros: The three assignments you do throughout the course are actually corrected by real humans and the feedback is very comprehensive. I liked that.

Still, udacity Business Analytics Nanodegree was not worth the money for me. The content of the course is very basic, particularly the Excel part contains so many bugs and it is also very poor didactically. Even from look and feel: Sheets used in the videos lack any formatting (how do you want the students to get used to using some basic color coding?). Some parts very so buggy, that I literally had the feeling somebody created the content right before I enrolled and I was the first user. 

I do not see any value add compared to e.g. udemy, which courses cost <20€ compared to 600€ at udacity.

headline: The program is really interesting so…
reviewBody:
The program is really interesting so far and the teacher Tyler really goes into detail and explains why and how things work behind the scenes to really strengthen the knowledge. It is also challenging at times which makes it fun to put time into and at the end complete the tasks or the quiz.

What I disliked so far was, that the little programming quizzes and takes don't often show why an answer is wrong. I sometimes wished for an explanation regarding the answers.
In addition, my code review of the first project "MyReads" was practically non-existent. It just had the rubric ticked on every aspect that I had got right. Also, I wrote what I liked to be looked at specifically inside the code, but threre was no comment on that. I just expected to get any comment at all on how I wrote the code and what could have done better regarding best practices.
Other than that, it is a great course so far.

headline: Incompetent Reviewers
reviewBody:
I submitted a project to be approved to run my Facebook ads and it was approved just fine. Now the second reviewer for the second project is telling me I did it completely wrong. They turned off the assignment submit feature on me where I couldn't submit anymore assignments.

I also submitted another assignment by accident that was CLEARLY wrong but it was approved just fine. I contacted Udacity about that too and never received a response.

I was supposed to be done with my course before the 5/25 deadline of being charged again.

So now I have spent hours of my time trying to complete a course and Udacity won't even let me finish to receive my Digital Marketing certificate.

I want a FREE course extension due to the incompetence of their reviewers but I can't even get a response back to my emails.

Don't waste your time and money. This is a scam company.

========================================

After a month of not responding to my emails and forcing me to make this review, this is their response:

Hello Elyse, 

Thanks for writing us back, unfortunately since you have cancelled your subscription for the nanodegree program, we can not offer a project submission extension.

Our apologizes for your experiences with the project review. We take the quality of project reviews seriously, and we are doing all we can to improve our quality. Project Reviewers are a vital part of the student experience and we always want to put forth our best when grading student projects.

I've passed along this information to our team, and we are thankful for your feedback.

All The Best,

Briauna Dotson
Program Coordinator, Services

========================================

My response:

You're not understanding. I would have been done with the nanodegree if it wasn't for your incompetent reviewers. Why should I have had to pay an extra $399 and wait almost a month for you to respond back to me?

It took you 3 weeks just to reset my assignment submission and you didn't even reset the second one I asked about so therefore I would have been paying an extra $800 due to two people's incompetence.

headline: C++ Nano-degree program Udacity
reviewBody: I enrolled for C++ Nano-degree program. The program is very well structured. The exercises and projects are very interesting and engaging. I knew C++ programming before starting the course but wasn't very well aware of the new C++11/14/17 concepts like move semantics, smart pointers, RAII, concurrency. Knowing these concepts of C++ is very important in today's world if you want to build something in C++ otherwise you can't appreciate the language much. The smart pointers concept requires more exercises and concept building in C++ nano-degree as it's one of the most complex concept to understand and apply. I did apply it in my capstone project - Asteroids shooting game as it makes life much more easier.

headline: It's OK
reviewBody:
I have recently completed two Udacity "nanodegree" courses: UX Design and Product Management. Here are my thoughts:
Pros:
1. Overall it's a good place to start for a beginner. Each course gave me a better understanding of what the jobs are about (something I couldn't find in short courses from coursera or udemy).  
2. The assignments are good and you have some freedom to choose your own topic in the UX course which is good. Grading is really fast - usually within 24h so you can move through the course quickly. 
3. Both courses took me about two months to complete. I was on the monthly payment plan and therefore motivated to finish them quickly. It's totally possible if you can spare 2-3 hours a day. 
4. Both courses also come with linkedin section where they teach you what to improve and give feedback on your edits. The UX course also teaches how to prepare case studies for your portfolio which I found really useful. 
5. There is a community around each course and each section has a micro-forum where you can ask questions if you're stuck. 

CONS:
1. Instructors. The course is structured in a typical way where you watch videos of your tutor speaking, then do a short quiz (not mandatory) and go to the next section. Instructors vary between course sections which makes it interesting. That being said some of the instructors are very poor. There are two instructors whose English is poor so they may be difficult to understand especially for a non-native speaker when even subtitles are incorrect. Some of the tutors seem to have the knowledge but not any presentation skills so getting through certain lessons was a real struggle. Some instructors made mistakes which were then marked on the video and I found that a bit lazy on the Udacity's side. Overall out of maybe 10 instructors, only 2 were engaging. 

2. Price. I took the advantage of their discounted monthly plan but if I'd paid over £800 per course I would have been very dissapointed due to poor delivery of the content. 

3. Navigation. The side navigation is a bit confusing at times and it's not possible to "untick" lessons as you go so I often found myself skipping lessons accidentaly. 

4. Feedback feels robotic. I have asked specific questions with my linkedin submission but the person never got back to me about those. This is also true for the assignments. They are graded fast but more of a copy-paste "great job, you have done xyz correctly!". I'd appreciate more personalised feedback. 

5. The whole "nanodegree" concept is just a maketing catchword that you should be aware of (in case you're not). It's got nothing to do with a degree, it's just a course but it's not even accredited. You get a PDF certificate but that's about it. I'm afraid it may be misleading to some. 

Hope this honest review will help you decide if Udacity is something for you. They have a free monthly trial now so you can always give it a go and see how you feel.

headline: The Front-End Development Nano-Degree…
reviewBody:
The Front-End Development Nano-Degree program itself is challenging, and i really like project oriented approach.
First, i like the teaching style. Basics --> your own research --> project --> review if necessary.
Unlike many other courses, based only on videos, this program makes you read the documentation and search for answers yourself. I consider these 2 aspects to be very important for a programmer.

Being able to ask good questions is of extreme importance in any field of Development. This program teaches you to ask GOOD questions, to meet the required project specifications.

I want to mention the Udacity's GUI, it looks and feels amazing.

Overall, the program and TA's give us great value and experience. Worth it.

headline: Udacity is a super modern way to learn
reviewBody:
Hi,
I'm from Croatia where the school system is pretty "old fashion" and not the most modern. Udacity should be an example of how modern schools should look like in the 21st Century. Udacity pays attention to every single detail in each lesson and the material is made so quality, that you really enjoy learning. On top of everything you have mentor support 24/7 and the student community is great too. I use to take some courses on Udemy, but it's so different than Udacity. Without doing the projects and practicing you have learned, you didn't do really too much to improve your skills. In my opinion, video, text and quiz content + projects make a great combination together.
I can just say one more thing "Good job Udacity"

headline: Best UX course
reviewBody:
I was looking around for over a month trying to decide which UX online course would suit me. I have 10 years of experience in this field so I wanted a course that could take me throughout an industry realistic process and it would help me fill the gaps. And that's exactly what I got from it. The curriculum is split in half between theory and hands-on exercises and gradually it exposes you to more difficult lessons and exercises. Everything a UX designer should know is covered, even more importantly, you know how everything connects.

One thing to keep in mind is that lessons don't contain as much in-depth content as a senior should know but that's a good thing because UX is a deep field and one might lose his interest. Instead, you gain a complete overview of everything and you can dig deeper afterwards.

You leave feeling prepared to work in the industry, unlike like other courses that seem to teach the same old generic BS lessons you can read for free on Medium.

headline: A moment for a 5-star review: iOS Nanodegree Program over a 30-day trial period
reviewBody:
This is a wonderful program in terms of its contents and instructional style. The materials are comprehensive, well-organized, and most importantly, make up a fun learning journey. The in-class exercises are very helpful and tie well with the projects required by the core curriculum. Most video lectures are short and accompanied by instructors' notes (or articles) that are easy to read and follow. 

Prior to enrolling in this program, I have had experience in Android programming as well as both recent academic and industry internship experience in data science. I would say, despite my extensive computational background, this course still challenged me and taught me transferrable skills through the Swift-iOS framework. For the 3 of 5 curriclum projects that I have submitted so far, I received constructive feedback from Udacity mentors. My Udacity reviewers really kept their expectations high and pushed for high-quality code + product. 

A few critiques for the sake of completeness: a few places where multiple sample apps are introduced and intertwined (e.g. UIKit & Networking lessons), it was a bit difficult to follow. Also, there seems to be some inconsistency in whether external links (e.g. GitHub repo, API websites, Apple Developer documentation) were provided. Nevertheless, these issues are rather minor, and I was able to digest the material by watching the lecture videos and associated notes more than once. 

Last but not least, I really appreciate Udacity's free 30-day trial period in the COVID-19 time when #stayhome is the best option for all. I only wish the program could be more affordable so that I could move along at a slower pace. Though it has been a "sprint" for me to get the most out of this nanodegree, this program has taught me quite a lot. Thus, I want give a moment to leave this program a 5-star review.

headline: Intro to iOS App Development with Swift - iOS Developer Nanodegree
reviewBody: The iOS Developer Nanodegrees curicculum is great so were the teachers so far. For sure one of the best programs I have taken online. The only thing that would have made it real 5 star "perfect" was if the videos could get updated with the latest version of Xcode which is v11 (instead of v9 which was used in Intro to iOS App dev with Swift course). This won't affect the quality of the learning materials much but it will lessen reasons for frustration and thereby increase the satisfaction and make better learning. Generally online courses should strive for faster update iterations. Other than that I enjoyed it a lot so far in the program, and absolutely better than others I have taken.

headline: Boon in quantitative education

headline: I lost a LOT of time in the beginning…
reviewBody: I lost a LOT of time in the beginning as I had overestimated the amount of energy I had after regular work. Then the Winter Holidays trip to EU didn't help with the momentum either. Now I am trying to catch up with the course. I feel I am learning a lot -- about ML but also the various tools like Anaconda, Jupyter, etc. I had never been a Python programmer; instead I've used C, C++, Java, Scala. I am open to Python but don't enjoy its lack of explicit type declaration. That cost me some lost time on the current project. Instead of doing np.dot(x, y), i wrote x.dot(y) -- thinking that the same function would be invoked. Python did not protest; MSE function got argument of a wrong type, but still computed something w/o protesting. Eventually, I figured out that the data types were wrong. Lesson learned!

headline: A.I Product Manager Nano Degree
reviewBody:
The first module was great. i learned following after completing my fist module.

• Understating the business problem and getting the right data to solve that problem is the most important and toughest job.
• Find an approach using A.I to solve business problem to get the solution.
• Come up with a strategy to get the data related to that problem
• Strategy to clean that data.
• Model selection process / approach.
• Need to have a clear path to deploy your model.
• Strategy how this model will integrate into business process.
• Some sort of monitoring process in production to check if your model is learning and acting the way it should be in production. There has to be a way to measure the success rate of your model.
• Come up with a measurable metric criteria. The metrics should be compare bale to competitor's numbers.

headline: Connections to Big Tech, but it doesn't show in the material
reviewBody: For the module on NoSQL databases, the materials and pointers are useful, but given it is a new and growing technology, to fully understand the use cases I would have appreciated a few real world examples (conceptual, rather than technical - say, a simple but informative diagram). For instance, an overview of how a company like Netflix uses Cassandra to retrieve and show movies to the subscribers when they interact with the search interface. How does the very practical, real-world action of clicking a button translates into architectural and data modeling choices? Udacity collaborates with many tech companies, you could leverage that connection to give us a better insight into their use of the technology and get a better feeling for how it could be applied.

headline: Your policy needs to be more empathetic
reviewBody:
Udacity's big promise is to offer people eager to learn an opportunity.

In short, and to make this brief – I am a paid customer to this moment, a brief incident happened with the payment while stopping the subscription for a certain course and subscribing for a new course.

While I was eager to start my new course, due to this incident, I lost access to the very last 1 week worth of learning of my previous course.

I asked the folks at Udacity if they can re-open up the older course for one or two weeks till I have the chance to finish that last part – They have asked me to renew the older course for 4 months (another 400+ Euros). I have paid over 900 Euros in total so far. All I got is that standard corporate, non-empathetic response of "Sorry, we can not help you, you must pay us more."

The question is, are you certain you can't really help a student here?

You, Udacity, obviously can help here, what harm will it bring to Udacity from re-opening a course for a student who is actually "still" paying you for just a couple weeks? I think your policy in place surely forgot that Udacity is about helping people learn. Be flexible with your students, and most importantly be flexible and helpful to your paid loyal customers.

You can surely help simply because re-opening will do you 0% harm in terms of costs you accrue. This is not a direct pricing relationship between computing power cost & usage. This is a relationship between content that's already prepared, and consumed by hundreds or thousands of students on a daily basis, therefore, it will never be of a harm to you.

You have a customer for the very short term, after I am done with this course, I will make sure that I'll neither ever return to your platform, nor ever recommend your platform as being student-centred to folks I know.

headline: I went into this course expecting to…
reviewBody:
I went into this course expecting to learn Python.
Having finished the course, I find I have learned a lot more:
•	Python (in-depth), 
•	Ndarrays, etc. using NumPy,
•	DataFrames, etc. using Pandas, 
•	Working with many other NoSQL structures
•	A more powerful SQL language: PostgreSQL
•	Unix Shell commands
•	Git

Perhaps even more importantly (and unexpectedly), I learned a bunch of really useful techniques to use in the coding world such as:
•	How to routinely work with other contributors using Git and GitHub, 
•	Using a Shell terminal with Git Bash and Anaconda packages,
•	Using code editors: Atom and Visual Studio Code, 
•	Using program output to feed Excel charts 
•	Using Excel charts to make compelling Powerpoint slides,
•	Adding links to Google and Markdown Docs, 
•	How to preview results in real time when writing Markdown docs, 
•	Creating good README.md files and many other best practices

The projects were well done and very effective in helping me apply the lessons learned in the course.  I especially appreciated the Python project using just under a million real-life records of bikeshare usage data.  After looking back and thinking about what I learned, to say that I highly recommend this course would be an understatement!
Dave A

headline: super poor
reviewBody: super poor, I scheduled two phone meeting, one is at night, one is at morning, I waited twice, no calling came in. I sent the support's email, after second time, he didn't reply anymore. Terrible experience, and when you send the email to the customer service, they never reply.

headline: Poor support
reviewBody: Training material is ok, and they send emails about progress but my issue is when for any reason you need to contact someone at Udacity. There's no phone number, just an email address that is either not monitored or the amount of email is so big there's no enough people to take care of issues. Also, if you have a question about the material you need to relay on a page that works kind of a forum, where you enter a question and just hope for someone to answer at some point. For the money I pay I'd expect to be able to reach to someone to get immediate answers about the topics, even if it's only during certain period of time.

headline: Extremely poor service
reviewBody:
I have enrolled in Udacity Deep Learning Nanodegree a year ago. I have paid full price beforehand.
After completing about 70% of the course I was unable to continue due to work commitments. Now I decided to continue, but Udacity does not allow me not only to continue the program but also access to the materials. When I signed up it clearly stated that I shall have access to the materials indefinitely.
I contacted support three times without any response.

headline: Udacity's content and support is not worth its money
reviewBody: Obviously a big part community of the nanodegree data foundations felt cheated. Content was not helpful at all. We were taught how to calculate am average(!), links where not working or just linking to wikipedia. Such a bad quality. The support just cared about their kpis to just make people click through and finish the course while promising to help afterwards. Well, it was a fraud. I believe udacity is discriminating transgenders. I would never spend any money here. I strongly recommmed other services.

headline: useless
reviewBody: useless, not well organized, few source of information. I have been trapped by believing the media propaganda about udacity. I have spent hours watching childlike courses about programming in java for android. It took me much less to do searches on google to learn to code application using javascript.

headline: Excellent classes, and service!
reviewBody: Udacity provides excellent service. Every video have some form of humour in it. There's always a great response and help from mentors and their video, and text content is easy to read, and understand.

headline: Love it! Wonderful resource for self-studying programming.
reviewBody: I LOVE Udacity -- it's my go-to website for any programming courses. The courses are all reviewed and certified, and I'm able to learn about programming at my pace. There is also an option to purchase the Nanodegrees if you're serious, but if you want to take it easy, you can take a programming course at no cost. The website interface is easy to use, and the only improvement I would suggest is to have more interaction between students.
